ngs separating from the fuselage. Structural failure due to severe turbulence during a thunderstorm. Pilots decision to descend without clearing the turbulent area of weather.','Near Ilheus, Brazil',30,1950,5,'spring',2),(1384,'1950-06-05 00:00:00','Atlantic Ocean off Florida','Westair Transport','Curtiss C-46-F-1-CU',65,28,0,'Ditched into the Atlantic 300 miles east of Melbourne, Florida on a flight from San Juan, Porto Rico to Wilmington, North Carolina due to failure of both engines. It sank in one of the deepest areas of the Atlantic and could not be recovered. Failure of both engines for reasons unknown.','Atlantic Ocean off Florida',5,1950,6,'summer',37),(1385,'1950-06-09 00:00:00','Near Fonseca, Colombia','New Tribes Mission','Douglas DC-3-178',15,15,0,'Struck trees, crashed and burned 19 miles east northeast of Fonseca well off course. Cause could not be determined.','Near Fonseca, Colombia',9,1950,6,'summer',0),(1387,'1950-06-14 00:00:00','Bahrain','Air France','Douglas DC-4',53,40,0,'On final approach at night, the aircraft hit the water surface and crashed into the Persian Gulf, few hundred yards short of the runway 29 threshold.','Off Bahrain',14,1950,6,'summer',13),(1389,'1950-06-23 00:00:00','Lake Michigan, 18 NNW of Benton Harbor, Michigan','Northwest Orient Airlines','Douglas DC-4',58,58,0,'En route from New York to Minneapolis, the aircraft crashed into Lake Michigan. The DC-4 was last reported at 3,500 ft. The crash occurred shortly after the aircraft entered an area of severe turbulence with thunderstorm activity. The wreckage was never found but was believed to be located in 150 feet of water and  not recoverable because it was in 30 feet of silt and an area of extremely poor visibility. The forecast of a squall line in the areas was not made available to the crew. Cause unknown.','Lake Michigan, 18 NNW of Benton Harbor, Michigan',23,1950,6,'summer',0),(1390,'1950-06-26 00:00:00','York, Australia','Ansett ANA','Douglas DC-4-1009',29,29,0,'The air