23,0,'The first takeoff attempt ended in an aborted takeoff due to engine boosting. This was not uncommon with this type of aircraft at higher altitudes and was usually caused the thrust being opened too fast. The second attempt to take off was aborted for the same reason. During the third attempt, as the plane passed V1 (committed to take off) the plane suddenly decelerated, never became airborne, crashed through the barrier fence, into a house and burst into flames. Eight members of the Manchester United football (soccer) team killed. A German inquiry concluded at an accumulation of ice on the wings was the cause of the accident, blaming the captain for not deicing the plane. Ten years later the British reopened the inquiry and concluded the accident was caused by slush on the last quarter of the runway. The reason other planes had taken off without incident was because they lifted in the air using only two thirds of the runway. The accident plane, because of the engine boosting, went further down the runway to take off. The aircraft was named \"Lord Burghley.\"','Munich, Germany',6,1958,2,'winter',21),(1966,'1958-02-15 00:00:00','Mount Vesuvius, Italy','Military - US Air Force','Douglas VC-47A',16,16,0,'Radio contact was lost with the military aircraft  thirty minutes after taking off from Naples after the crew reported en route at 6,500 feet and switching to the Rome ATC. The plane crashed on the northern slopes of Mt. Vesuvius.','Mount Vesuvius, Italy',15,1958,2,'winter',0),(1967,'1958-02-19 00:00:00','Raiatea, French Polynesia','Réseau Aérien Interinsulaire','Consolidated PBY-5A  Catalina',15,15,0,'Struck the water and sank after the right wing tip float contacted the water during a shallow turn for final approach.','Cairo, Egypt',19,1958,2,'winter',0),(1968,'1958-02-19 00:00:00','Raiatea, French Polynesia','Réseau Aérien Interinsulaire','Consolidated PBY-5A  Catalina',15,15,0,'Struck the water and sank after the right wing tip float contacted the water during