he person who closed it was an engineer who was not listed among those (in the Cabin Attendant Manual) who were supposed to close the door.  A report concludes that the aircraft originally lost cabin pressure due to this. 1) Failure of the crew to maintain proper crew resource management and cooperation in flight\r2) Failure to maintain visual contact with the runway or visual approach aids during a visual approach\r3) Loss of control with regards to height while doing the orbit necessary due to miscalculation of the landing performance and estimated landing trajectory 4) Failure to respond correctly to the TAWS alert (Terrain Awareness and Alerting System).','Near Cabañas, Guatemala',24,2008,8,'summer',22),(5703,'2008-08-30 00:00:00','Near Toacaso, Ecuador','Conviasa','Boeing B-737-291',3,3,0,'The plane was on a positioning flight when it flew into the side of Iliniza Volcano.','Near Toacaso, Ecuador',30,2008,8,'summer',0),(5704,'2008-09-01 00:00:00','Columbus, Ohio','Air Tahoma','Convair CV-580',3,3,0,'Soon after taking off the pilot radioed he was returning to the airport but the aircraft crashed into a corn field, broke up and burned. The improper (reverse) rigging of the elevator trim cables by company maintenance personnel, and their subsequent failure to discover the misrigging during required post-maintenance checks. Contributing to the accident was the captain’s inadequate post-maintenance preflight check.','Near Bukavu, Congo',1,2008,9,'autumn',0),(5705,'2008-09-01 00:00:00','Columbus, Ohio','Air Tahoma','Convair CV-580',3,3,0,'Soon after taking off the pilot radioed he was returning to the airport but the aircraft crashed into a corn field, broke up and burned. The improper (reverse) rigging of the elevator trim cables by company maintenance personnel, and their subsequent failure to discover the misrigging during required post-maintenance checks. Contributing to the accident was the captain’s inadequate post-maintenance preflight check.','Columbus, Ohio'